<div class="container py-5">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-lg-8">
      <h1 class="mb-4">Women's Cancer Awareness</h1>
      <p class="lead mb-4">Early detection saves lives. Learn about cancers that commonly affect women, risk factors, screening guidelines, and prevention strategies.</p>
      
      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Breast Cancer</h5>
          
          <div class="row mb-4">
            <div class="col-md-8">
              <p>Breast cancer is the most common cancer in women worldwide. It occurs when cells in the breast grow out of control. These cells usually form a tumor that can be felt as a lump or seen on an x-ray.</p>
              
              <h6 class="mt-3">Risk Factors</h6>
              <ul>
                <li>Being female and increasing age</li>
                <li>Personal or family history of breast cancer</li>
                <li>Inherited gene mutations (BRCA1 and BRCA2)</li>
                <li>Dense breast tissue</li>
                <li>Early menstruation (before age 12) or late menopause (after 55)</li>
                <li>Having never been pregnant or having first pregnancy after age 30</li>
                <li>Postmenopausal hormone therapy</li>
                <li>Alcohol consumption</li>
              </ul>
              
              <h6 class="mt-3">Screening Recommendations</h6>
              <p><strong>Ages 40-44:</strong> Optional annual mammogram<br>
              <strong>Ages 45-54:</strong> Annual mammogram<br>
              <strong>Ages 55+:</strong> Mammogram every 1-2 years</p>
              
              <div class="alert alert-info">
                <i class="fas fa-info-circle me-2"></i> Women at high risk may need earlier or more frequent screening. Consult your healthcare provider for personalized recommendations.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-4">
              <div class="text-center">
                <i class="fas fa-ribbon fa-6x mb-3 text-danger"></i>
                <p class="small text-muted">Pink ribbon: international symbol for breast cancer awareness</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <h6>Signs and Symptoms</h6>
          <div class="row mb-3">
            <div class="col-md-6">
              <ul>
                <li>New lump in the breast or underarm</li>
                <li>Thickening or swelling of part of the breast</li>
                <li>Irritation or dimpling of breast skin</li>
                <li>Redness or flaky skin in the nipple area or breast</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-6">
              <ul>
                <li>Pulling in of the nipple or pain in the nipple area</li>
                <li>Nipple discharge other than breast milk</li>
                <li>Any change in the size or shape of the breast</li>
                <li>Pain in any area of the breast</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <div class="alert alert-warning">
            <strong>Remember:</strong> Many breast changes are not cancer, but it's important to have any changes checked by a healthcare provider.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Cervical Cancer</h5>
          
          <div class="row mb-4">
            <div class="col-md-8">
              <p>Cervical cancer begins in the cells of the cervix, the lower part of the uterus that connects to the vagina. It is almost always caused by human papillomavirus (HPV) infection.</p>
              
              <h6 class="mt-3">Risk Factors</h6>
              <ul>
                <li>HPV infection</li>
                <li>Smoking</li>
                <li>Weakened immune system</li>
                <li>Sexual history (multiple partners, early sexual activity)</li>
                <li>Long-term use of birth control pills</li>
                <li>Having many children</li>
              </ul>
              
              <h6 class="mt-3">Screening Recommendations</h6>
              <p><strong>Ages 21-29:</strong> Pap test every 3 years<br>
              <strong>Ages 30-65:</strong> Pap test and HPV test every 5 years, or Pap test alone every 3 years<br>
              <strong>After 65:</strong> Screening may be discontinued if prior screenings were normal</p>
              
              <div class="alert alert-success">
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle me-2"></i> Cervical cancer is one of the most preventable types of cancer through HPV vaccination and regular screening.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-4">
              <div class="text-center">
                <i class="fas fa-ribbon fa-6x mb-3 text-teal"></i>
                <p class="small text-muted">Teal and white ribbon: symbol for cervical cancer awareness</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <h6>Signs and Symptoms</h6>
          <ul>
            <li>Abnormal vaginal bleeding (after intercourse, between periods, after menopause)</li>
            <li>Unusual vaginal discharge</li>
            <li>Pain during intercourse</li>
            <li>Pelvic pain</li>
            <li>In advanced stages: severe back pain, weight loss, fatigue, leg pain or swelling</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Ovarian Cancer</h5>
          
          <div class="row mb-4">
            <div class="col-md-8">
              <p>Ovarian cancer begins in the ovaries, the female reproductive glands. It often goes undetected until it has spread within the pelvis and abdomen, making it difficult to treat and often fatal.</p>
              
              <h6 class="mt-3">Risk Factors</h6>
              <ul>
                <li>Age (most common after menopause)</li>
                <li>Family history of ovarian, breast, or colorectal cancer</li>
                <li>Gene mutations (BRCA1, BRCA2, Lynch syndrome)</li>
                <li>Never having been pregnant</li>
                <li>Endometriosis</li>
                <li>Early menstruation or late menopause</li>
                <li>Hormone replacement therapy after menopause</li>
              </ul>
              
              <h6 class="mt-3">Screening</h6>
              <p>Currently, there is no recommended screening test for average-risk women without symptoms. Women at high risk should discuss screening options with their healthcare provider.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-4">
              <div class="text-center">
                <i class="fas fa-ribbon fa-6x mb-3 text-info"></i>
                <p class="small text-muted">Teal ribbon: symbol for ovarian cancer awareness</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <h6>Signs and Symptoms</h6>
          <p>Early symptoms can be vague and similar to other common conditions:</p>
          <div class="row">
            <div class="col-md-6">
              <ul>
                <li>Abdominal bloating or swelling</li>
                <li>Quickly feeling full when eating</li>
                <li>Weight loss</li>
                <li>Discomfort in the pelvic area</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-6">
              <ul>
                <li>Changes in bowel habits (constipation)</li>
                <li>Frequent need to urinate</li>
                <li>Persistent fatigue</li>
                <li>Unexplained back pain</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <div class="alert alert-warning mt-3">
            <strong>Remember the BEAT symptoms:</strong><br>
            <strong>B</strong> - Bloating that is persistent<br>
            <strong>E</strong> - Eating less and feeling fuller<br>
            <strong>A</strong> - Abdominal or pelvic pain<br>
            <strong>T</strong> - Trouble with bladder or bowels
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Endometrial (Uterine) Cancer</h5>
          
          <div class="row mb-4">
            <div class="col-md-8">
              <p>Endometrial cancer begins in the lining of the uterus (endometrium). It is the most common gynecologic cancer in the United States.</p>
              
              <h6 class="mt-3">Risk Factors</h6>
              <ul>
                <li>Age (most cases diagnosed after menopause)</li>
                <li>Obesity</li>
                <li>Estrogen therapy without progesterone</li>
                <li>Late menopause (after age 55)</li>
                <li>Never having been pregnant</li>
                <li>Diabetes</li>
                <li>History of polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS)</li>
                <li>Family history of endometrial, colorectal, or ovarian cancer</li>
                <li>Lynch syndrome</li>
              </ul>
              
              <h6 class="mt-3">Screening</h6>
              <p>There is no standard screening test for endometrial cancer in women without symptoms. Women at high risk may need endometrial sampling periodically.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-4">
              <div class="text-center">
                <i class="fas fa-ribbon fa-6x mb-3 text-light bg-dark p-3 rounded"></i>
                <p class="small text-muted">Peach ribbon: symbol for endometrial cancer awareness</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <h6>Signs and Symptoms</h6>
          <ul>
            <li>Abnormal vaginal bleeding (especially after menopause)</li>
            <li>Bleeding between periods</li>
            <li>Pelvic pain</li>
            <li>Painful urination</li>
            <li>Pain during intercourse</li>
            <li>Unexplained weight loss</li>
          </ul>
          
          <div class="alert alert-danger mt-3">
            <i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle me-2"></i> <strong>Warning:</strong> Any abnormal bleeding after menopause should be reported to your healthcare provider immediately, as it is the most common symptom of endometrial cancer.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    
    <div class="col-lg-4 mt-4 mt-lg-0">
      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Risk Reduction Strategies</h5>
          
          <div class="d-flex align-items-center mb-3">
            <div class="me-3">
              <i class="fas fa-apple-alt fa-2x text-success"></i>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h6 class="mb-0">Maintain a Healthy Diet</h6>
              <p class="small mb-0">Eat plenty of fruits, vegetables, and whole grains. Limit processed foods, red meat, and alcohol.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <div class="d-flex align-items-center mb-3">
            <div class="me-3">
              <i class="fas fa-running fa-2x text-primary"></i>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h6 class="mb-0">Exercise Regularly</h6>
              <p class="small mb-0">Aim for at least 150 minutes of moderate activity or 75 minutes of vigorous activity weekly.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <div class="d-flex align-items-center mb-3">
            <div class="me-3">
              <i class="fas fa-weight fa-2x text-warning"></i>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h6 class="mb-0">Maintain Healthy Weight</h6>
              <p class="small mb-0">Obesity increases risk for several cancers including breast, endometrial, and ovarian.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <div class="d-flex align-items-center mb-3">
            <div class="me-3">
              <i class="fas fa-smoking-ban fa-2x text-danger"></i>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h6 class="mb-0">Avoid Tobacco</h6>
              <p class="small mb-0">Smoking increases risk for many cancers. Get help to quit if needed.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <div class="d-flex align-items-center mb-3">
            <div class="me-3">
              <i class="fas fa-syringe fa-2x text-info"></i>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h6 class="mb-0">Get HPV Vaccination</h6>
              <p class="small mb-0">Protects against most cervical cancers and some other HPV-related cancers.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <div class="d-flex align-items-center">
            <div class="me-3">
              <i class="fas fa-stethoscope fa-2x text-secondary"></i>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h6 class="mb-0">Regular Check-ups</h6>
              <p class="small mb-0">Follow recommended screening guidelines and report any unusual symptoms to your doctor.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">How to Perform a Breast Self-Exam</h5>
          
          <div class="accordion" id="breastExamAccordion">
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingStep1">
                <button class="accordion-button" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseStep1" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="collapseStep1">
                  Step 1: Visual Inspection
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseStep1" class="accordion-collapse collapse show" aria-labelledby="headingStep1" data-bs-parent="#breastExamAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <p>Stand in front of a mirror with your shoulders straight and arms on your hips.</p>
                  <p>Look for:</p>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Changes in size, shape, or color</li>
                    <li>Dimpling, puckering, or bulging of the skin</li>
                    <li>Nipple changes (position, inversion)</li>
                    <li>Redness, soreness, rash, or swelling</li>
                  </ul>
                  <p>Repeat with arms raised and while leaning forward.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingStep2">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseStep2" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseStep2">
                  Step 2: Lying Down
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseStep2" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingStep2" data-bs-parent="#breastExamAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <p>Lie down and place a pillow under your right shoulder. Put your right arm behind your head.</p>
                  <p>Use the finger pads of your left hand to feel for lumps in the right breast. Use a firm, smooth touch and a circular motion, covering the entire breast from collarbone to abdomen, and from armpit to cleavage.</p>
                  <p>Repeat on the left breast using your right hand.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingStep3">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseStep3" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseStep3">
                  Step 3: Sitting or Standing
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseStep3" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingStep3" data-bs-parent="#breastExamAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <p>Feel your breasts while sitting or standing, with one arm slightly raised. Many women find this easiest in the shower when the skin is wet and slippery.</p>
                  <p>Use the same hand movements described in Step 2.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingStep4">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseStep4" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseStep4">
                  Step 4: Nipple Exam
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseStep4" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingStep4" data-bs-parent="#breastExamAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  <p>Gently squeeze each nipple to check for discharge.</p>
                  <p>Note any changes in the nipple, including discharge that occurs without squeezing.</p>
                  <div class="alert alert-info">
                    <i class="fas fa-info-circle me-2"></i> Perform your breast self-exam once a month, preferably 7-10 days after your period starts when your breasts are least likely to be tender or swollen.
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
